Answers:

  1. The results are fairly inconsistent. The cluster center changes location frequently, and the cluster assignments vary considerably. Sometimes, there are pretty dramatic variations such that the data go from being split horizontally to being split vertically. Ive attached an example of one dramatic variation:
grid.arrange(plot1,plot2, ncol=2)

As we can see, the cluster centers are in noticeably different positions, given the different assignment of clusters to data points. In one case, there is a horizontal partition, while in the second, there is a vertical one.

We are attempting to find two reasonably distinctive groups in the dataset. However, since the divisions between the points arent necessarily super clear and there is substantial overlap, it becomes hard to figure out whether the points in the middle are dissimilar to one another (and harder to figure out which cluster they belong to). Thus, cluster assignment in such unclear settings can be fairly arbitrary.

The results are pretty consistent. Running the code many times doesnt change the general identification of two distinct clusters roughly separated across the diagonal \(y = 2 - x\).

plot3

The data are more cleanly partitioned in observations 2, with a diagonal line separating two discernable groups. Since we have, by setting K=2, told the algorithm to find two groups such that within group similarity and between group dissimilarity are high, assigning data points into clusters across the diagonal makes sense.

Bonus question: Code your own

Read ISLR page 388 Algorithm 10.1 and implement k-means clustering from scratch. Dont worry about doing it for general \(k\); keep it simple and do it for \(k=2\) specifically. Apply it to observations_2 from above.

General Algorithm:

  1. Randomly Assign every observation to either cluster 1 or 2
  2. Compute cluster center
  3. Reassign every observation to either cluster 1 or 2 based on :
  1. if distance b/w point and cluster 1 center is smaller than distance b/w point and cluster 2 center, assign point to cluster 1
  2. otherwise assign point to cluster 2
  1. Repeat until results dont change i.e.until a local optimum is reached.
observations<-observations_2

cluster<-sample(1:2, nrow(observations),replace=TRUE) #randomly assign clusters
initial<-data.frame(observations,cluster)
cent1<- initial %>% 
  group_by(cluster) %>% 
  summarize(mean(x1), mean (x2)) #get the mean values for each cluster
clustercenters<- cent1[2:3]

distance_matrix <- proxy::dist(x=observations, y=clustercenters) #Find distance b/w each point and both cluster centers

observations$cluster <- as.factor(cluster)

cluster_centers <- clustercenters %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  mutate(cluster=as.factor(1:k))
cluster_centers<-cluster_centers %>% 
  rename(x1=`mean(x1)`, x2 =`mean(x2)`)

plot4<-ggplot(NULL, aes(x=x1, y=x2, col=cluster)) +
geom_point(data=observations) +
 geom_point(data=cluster_centers, size=5)
plot4

cluster<-apply(distance_matrix, 1, which.min) #Find which cluster center each value is closest to.
observations<-data.frame(observations,cluster) #reassign clusters
observations <- observations[,-3]

cent2<- observations %>% 
  group_by(cluster.1) %>% 
  summarize(mean(x1), mean (x2)) #get the mean values for each cluster
clustercenters<- cent2[2:3]

observations$cluster <- as.factor(cluster)
cluster_centers <- clustercenters %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  mutate(cluster=as.factor(1:k))
cluster_centers<-cluster_centers %>% 
  rename(x1=`mean(x1)`, x2 =`mean(x2)`)

plot5<-ggplot(NULL, aes(x=x1, y=x2, col=cluster)) +
          geom_point(data=observations) +
        geom_point(data=cluster_centers, size=5)

plot5

We can see how, in just two iterations, the algorithm creates two reasonably distinct clusters in Observations_2.
